---
description: Require public intent docs and parameter documentation in source code
alwaysApply: true
---

# Public Code Documentation Rule

All source code must include public documentation that explains intent and behavior.

## Required documentation for changed/new code

- Every public source file must include a short top-level doc comment describing:
  - the file's intent,
  - the main responsibilities,
  - important side effects (if any).
- Every package directory under `frontend/src/` must include a `README.md` that explains:
  - the package purpose,
  - the most important modules, exports, types, or subdirectories it contains,
  - how those important modules are used by the rest of the app,
  - the main ownership or boundary expectations for that package,
  - whether the package is canonical, transitional, or a compatibility facade.
- Every public function/method must include a doc comment that explains:
  - purpose and behavior,
  - all parameters (name, meaning, and expected shape/range),
  - return value,
  - side effects and error behavior when relevant.
- For classes/components/modules, document the integration, configuration, and communication APIs.

## Readability and usefulness standard

- Documentation must be actionable for maintainers, not just structurally complete.
- Prefer concrete phrasing:
  - name real functions/exports/callbacks,
  - name real files and subdirectories when documenting a package,
  - call out the most important types/state shapes/components/hooks in that package,
  - name real configuration keys and where they are passed,
  - name real side effects (state fields, DOM writes, storage/network calls).
- Avoid vague, content-light phrasing (for example "delegates to services", "supports communication", "handles configuration") unless followed by concrete details.
- Write with "how to use this module" in mind: what to call, what to pass, what happens.

## Package README minimum standard

Package `README.md` files under `frontend/src/` must be useful to a developer who has not
already read the package source.

- Every package README must include:
  - a one-paragraph purpose/boundary summary,
  - a short list of the most important files, exports, types, or subdirectories,
  - a short explanation of how those files/exports are typically used,
  - guidance on what code belongs in the package and what should live elsewhere.
- Small or transitional packages must still explain why they exist.
  - Example: if a directory only contains two hooks, the README must name those hooks and
    explain why they remain shared rather than feature-owned.
  - Example: if a directory is a facade or compatibility layer, the README must say what the
    canonical package is and whether new code should still be added there.
- Avoid placeholder summaries that only restate the directory name.
  - Bad: "Contains shared helpers."
  - Good: "Contains `session_state_sync.ts` for mirroring `GameSessionState` into reducer
    actions, and `useTauriMenu.ts` for installing the desktop menu from
    `app/shell/menu_definition.ts`."

## Parameter documentation policy

- Document all parameters explicitly; do not skip optional/defaulted parameters.
- For callbacks, document callback signature and when it is invoked.
- For structured objects, document expected keys and constraints.

## JSDoc format for exported functions

Use JSDoc tags on all exported functions, hook factories, and factory functions.

- `@param name Description` for every parameter. Omit `{type}` — TypeScript types
  are the authoritative declaration.
- `@returns Description` when the return value is non-void.
- No `@param` or `@returns` on exported **type aliases** and **interfaces** — use
  inline field comments instead.
- File-level Integration / Configuration / Communication API comments satisfy the
  module-level doc requirement and need not be repeated per-function.
- No-parameter hooks returning a named state type still require `@returns` with a
  one-line description of what the state object exposes; the type name alone is
  not sufficient.

## Delivery checks before finalizing changes

- New/updated source files include top-level intent comments.
- New/updated public functions and methods include parameter docs.
- Documentation reflects current behavior after refactors.
- Top-level component docs are concrete enough that another developer can integrate the component without opening unrelated files.
- Package `README.md` files are added for new packages and updated whenever a refactor changes package ownership, directory responsibilities, or canonical import paths.
- Package `README.md` files are not left as thin placeholders; they must identify the important
  files/types/subdirectories that a maintainer will look for first.
